node.text:
At what point is too much government intervention bad for the economy? Rep. 
@reprokhanna and I debate. I can't think of a more important conversation to be having right now! @cnbc

node.title: The economy is on fire, is now the time to hit it with more government?

node.text: Corporate tax rates are how nations compete for business. The better run counties charge lower tax rates and get the jobs that help grow their economies. Trying to set a minimum corporate tax rate of 15% is just old fashioned price fixing. Its a very bad Idea. Let nations compete for capital and jobs. Competition and innovation is what keeps the economy growing not more taxes!

node.title: Price Fixing Corporate Tax Rates Is Bad For Our Economy

node.text: My mother Georgette was the first woman - the first person really - who taught me that with perseverance, patience, and passion, you can achieve anything.  The embodiment of strength. I am thankful for her, and all the women in my life today - in family, in business, and friendship who continue to inspire in the same way she did!

node.text:
People love asking me if I think an MBA, or a diploma in general, is worth the expense. My answer, as an MBA graduate? An MBA might make you smarter but it won't make you more successful. Look at Mark Zuckerberg, Bill Gates - two of countless college drop outs who made it big on an astronomical level. Not everyone needs an expensive higher education to be successful. In some cases, it's a waste of money 

THAT SAID. For a 20-something like me with dyslexia, and quite frankly awful study habits, my MBA gave me a head start & more importantly, DISCIPLINE.

It helped develop my limited attention span. I learned how to defend an idea - a skill I didn't have before. I'd always had a big mouth, but my opinions were uninformed and often unchallenged. Over the course of my secondary education I stuffed my toolbox with valuable skills. I learned how to make money from the things I was good at. I learned how to focus on my strengths and deflect from my weaknesses. I learned how to select and work with ideal partners. BUT I still hadn't achieved a very important entrepreneurial goal: I still hadn't earned a dime for anyone else. 

That's one thing a MBA wont' guarantee
